<dl id="n03143f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03143f">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03143f"> 143(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Is blushes <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03143f"> <li>FW isotext &nbsp;fn101 </li><li><ms href="#n03143f">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="led0" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#led0">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/le/led0.htm#n03143f">Draft: II.2&sect;6.0</a>&chi; </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Transferred via <a name="sh2014d" href="sh2all.htm#sh2014d">Sheet ii-14(d)</a>. Not in final text. </mm> <blockquote class="sources">But the felons came up and said: &ldquo;King, harken to the counsel we give thee in all loyalty. The Queen was wrongfully slandered, we confess; but if she and Tristram return together to the court, there will be more evil talk. Let Tristram go away for a season; one day no doubt thou wilt recall him.&rdquo; / Mark did so; he commanded Tristram by his barons to go without delay. Then Tristram approached the Queen, and bade her farewell. The Queen was ashamed because of the assembly, and <mark>she blushed</mark>. But the King was moved to pity, and speaking to his nephew for the first time, he said: &ldquo;Where wilt thou go in these rags? Take from my treasury all things needed for thee, gold and silver, and vair.&rdquo; <small> Joseph B&eacute;dier, <a name="JBLR1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JBLR1"><cite title="source">Le roman de Tristan et Iseut</cite></a> (1900) XI &lsquo;Le Gu&eacute; Aventureux&rsquo;, 127 [The Ford Perilous, 125]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
